  <!-- Section: Common Mistakes -->
  <section id="mistakes" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Forgetting to Validate VLS-TS</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">The most critical mistake. You must validate your VLS-TS visa online within 3 months of arrival at the ANEF portal. Missing this deadline invalidates your visa and creates serious legal problems. Do it in your first week in France.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Skipping Campus France</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">If your country requires Campus France procedure, you cannot skip it. Your visa application will be rejected without the Campus France attestation. Start this process early—it takes 2-6 weeks minimum.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Not Applying for CAF</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Many students don't know about or forget to apply for CAF housing assistance (APL). You're eligible regardless of nationality. Apply at caf.fr after signing your lease—you could receive €100-200/month. It's free money.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Underestimating Paris Costs</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Paris is expensive. The €615/month minimum is unrealistic for Paris—budget €1,000-1,400/month realistically. Consider other cities (Lyon, Bordeaux, Toulouse, Lille) if budget is a concern—quality education, lower costs.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Skipping Mutuelle Without Understanding Costs</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Social Security covers 70%, you pay 30%. For a hospital stay or specialist care, 30% can add up fast. A mutuelle at €15-30/month is cheap insurance against unexpected medical costs. Consider your risk tolerance.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Healthcare in France -->
  <section id="healthcare" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Healthcare in France</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      France has one of the world's best healthcare systems, ranking #1 in the WHO's global assessment. As a student with Social Security coverage, you have access to this excellent system at minimal cost.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">What's Covered by Social Security</h3>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-6">
      <div class="border border-green-200 bg-green-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-green-900 mb-3">70% Covered (Sécu Only)</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-green-800">
          <li>✓ Doctor consultations (GP and specialists)</li>
          <li>✓ Hospital stays</li>
          <li>✓ Prescription medications</li>
          <li>✓ Lab tests and imaging</li>
          <li>✓ Mental health (with referral)</li>
          <li>✓ Basic dental care</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="border border-blue-200 bg-blue-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-blue-900 mb-3">100% with Mutuelle</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-blue-800">
          <li>✓ Full reimbursement (no out-of-pocket)</li>
          <li>✓ Better optical coverage</li>
          <li>✓ Better dental coverage</li>
          <li>✓ Alternative medicine (some plans)</li>
          <li>✓ Private hospital rooms (some plans)</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">How to Access Healthcare</h3>

    <div class="space-y-4 mb-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Step 1: Get Your Carte Vitale</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">After CVEC registration, apply for your Carte Vitale (health card) through ameli.fr. Processing takes 2-4 weeks. In the meantime, doctors will provide paper forms for reimbursement.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Step 2: Find a Doctor</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Search for a médecin traitant (primary doctor) on doctolib.fr or annuairesante.ameli.fr. You can see doctors without a referral, but having a médecin traitant improves reimbursement rates.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Step 3: Book Appointments</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Use Doctolib (app or website) to book most appointments. Some doctors accept walk-ins. University health centers (SUMPPS) offer free services for students.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Emergencies</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Call 15 (SAMU) for medical emergencies or 112 (European emergency number). Go to hospital urgences (emergency room) for serious issues. SOS Médecins provides house calls for non-emergencies.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-4 mt-6">
      <p class="text-blue-800">
        <strong>University health services:</strong> Most French universities have SUMPPS (Service Universitaire de Médecine Préventive et de Promotion de la Santé) offering free medical consultations, mental health support, and preventive care. Use these—they're included in your CVEC.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Do I need private health insurance for the France student visa?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          No. Since 2019, students are automatically enrolled in French Social Security through the CVEC contribution (€100/year). This replaces the old requirement for separate student insurance. A mutuelle (top-up) is optional but recommended to cover the 30% not covered by Social Security.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What is Campus France and do I need it?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Campus France is the French government agency managing international student applications. Most non-EU students must complete the "Études en France" procedure before applying for a visa. It validates your academic project and simplifies applications. Check if your country requires it.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What is a mutuelle and should I get one?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          A mutuelle is complementary insurance covering the 30% of costs not covered by Social Security. Without it, you pay 30% out of pocket for medical care. Student mutuelles cost €15-50/month and provide peace of mind. Highly recommended, especially for glasses, dental, or regular medical needs.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What is CAF and how do I get housing benefits?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          CAF (Caisse d'Allocations Familiales) provides housing assistance (APL) to students regardless of nationality. Apply at caf.fr after signing your lease. Depending on your rent and situation, you could receive €100-200/month. It takes 2-3 months to process, but payments are retroactive.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I work while studying in France?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes. Students can work up to 964 hours per year (about 20 hours/week) without a separate work permit. During summer, you can work more. The French minimum wage (SMIC) is €11.65/hour. Your student residence card includes work authorization.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I stay after graduation?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes. After completing a master's or higher degree, you can apply for an APS (Autorisation Provisoire de Séjour)—a temporary residence permit to search for work. If you find a job matching your qualifications, you can switch to a work permit. Not as generous as Germany's 18 months, but workable.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

